On Escalation Ticket # 00412676 the new comment has been added: Ethan Israel:

@Salesforce @Helen Randall - Dev investigated the missing groups issue and it looks like the issue here is the scoping they have configured on the Effective Access Report in the AIC. They have "No nesting" applied in the scope (see "nesting scope.png" attached in SP). Please have them adjust the nesting scope and try again. 

The fact that those trustees are showing null in T2 seems to be a red herring. We keep minimum membership details for the trustees in the tier 2 database. For reports, we get this detailed information from Entra ID Inventory.

If they're still not seeing the expected data after adjusting the nesting scope, please ask them to verify the membership chain by executing queries for the missing group(s) on the following views and share the results with us,

[dbo].[SA_AzureADInventory_GroupMembersView]

[dbo].[SA_AzureADInventory_EffectiveGroupMembersView]

[DevOps CommentId:10925058]

On Escalation Ticket # 00412676 the new comment has been added: We increased scope of nesting level and that did not do the trick. A user that is a member of 'zzNon-Employee-CRO-SponsorVendor' (which is an on-prem AD group synced to Entra ID), is not showing as having access to any of the site collections that the 'Medpace Read' SPO group has access to, and the 'zzNon-Employee-CRO-SponsorVendor' group is a member of the 'Medpace Read' group. Customer ran queries against SA_AzureADInventory_GroupMembersView and SA_AzureADInventory_EffectiveGroupMembersView targeting both groups and attached results to excel spreadsheet now attached to ticket (AIC_9_16_2024.xlsx). They got no results back from either view for the 'Medpace Read' SPO group.

On Escalation Ticket # 00412676 the new comment has been added: Adam DeSapio:

@Chris Brooks @Michael Burrofato @Helen Randall @Salesforce

It looks like their SPAC bulk imports still have the <DisableActivityResourceManager> setting set to true, but their SPAA scans have the setting set to false.
They should always be the same.
One issue that is happening right now is SPAC imports are importing new data that needs to be resolved, but since the setting is turned off, they will never be resolved.
That means every SPAA/SPSEEK scan will have more and more data to look up/add during the slow ActivityResourceManager step.

Turning that setting to false for SPAC BI will cause activity data that was previously added to get resolved, thus requiring fewer lookups / inserts at the start of the next SPAA scan.
